(2288, 1, '2014-12-18 06:41:21', '2014-12-18 06:41:21', '[two_third]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe debate over the juxtaposition of population issue and poverty may be almost as old as population itself and, in the view of the increasing trend tow­ards its complete regulation. Not surprisingly, and is generally recognized by contemporary writers on this topic, the philosophical and moral arguments for or against population issue/s have remained remarkably unchanged since the beginning of the debate.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“For the most part of the past century, the Philippine economy performed poorly, especially against the backdrop of the dynamic East Asian economies. Spurts of growth were often followed by bust and stagnation. Not surprisingly absolute poverty among a significant proportion of the population has persisted. The country’s real per capita GDP at the turn of the 21<sup>st</sup> century was just about the same as that in the early 1980s, which also is partly attributed to unabated population growth” (ArsenioBalicsan, Ernesto Pernia ERD Policy Brief No.5 Issued February 2002).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere is an existing rift; on one side, there are those who state that there is no existing population problem and, therefore that there is no need to act or study it. On the other, some view population growth as the principal cause of poverty.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPoverty is a vast complex phenomenon, and many factors are responsible for it. Rapid population growth alone cannot explain poverty. Bad governance, high wealth and income inequality and weak economic growth rate are the main cause. But rapid population growth and fertility rates, especially among the poor exacerbates it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[/two_third]', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-18 06:41:21', '2014-12-18 06:41:21', '', 5, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2288', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2289, 1, '2014-12-18 06:44:10', '2014-12-18 06:44:10', '[two_third]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">The debate over the juxtaposition of population issue and poverty may be almost as old as population itself and, in the view of the increasing trend tow­ards its complete regulation. Not surprisingly, and is generally recognized by contemporary writers on this topic, the philosophical and moral arguments for or against population issue/s have remained remarkably unchanged since the beginning of the debate.</span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;"> </span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">“For the most part of the past century, the Philippine economy performed poorly, especially against the backdrop of the dynamic East Asian economies. Spurts of growth were often followed by bust and stagnation. Not surprisingly absolute poverty among a significant proportion of the population has persisted. The country’s real per capita GDP at the turn of the 21<sup>st</sup> century was just about the same as that in the early 1980s, which also is partly attributed to unabated population growth” (ArsenioBalicsan, Ernesto Pernia ERD Policy Brief No.5 Issued February 2002).</span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;"> </span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">There is an existing rift; on one side, there are those who state that there is no existing population problem and, therefore that there is no need to act or study it. On the other, some view population growth as the principal cause of poverty.</span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;"> </span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">Poverty is a vast complex phenomenon, and many factors are responsible for it. Rapid population growth alone cannot explain poverty. Bad governance, high wealth and income inequality and weak economic growth rate are the main cause. But rapid population growth and fertility rates, especially among the poor exacerbates it.</span></h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[/two_third]', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-18 06:44:10', '2014-12-18 06:44:10', '', 5, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2289', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2290, 1, '2014-12-18 06:45:22', '2014-12-18 06:45:22', '[two_third]\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">The debate over the juxtaposition of population issue and poverty may be almost as old as population itself and, in the view of the increasing trend tow­ards its complete regulation. Not surprisingly, and is generally recognized by contemporary writers on this topic, the philosophical and moral arguments for or against population issue/s have remained remarkably unchanged since the beginning of the debate.</span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;"> </span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">“For the most part of the past century, the Philippine economy performed poorly, especially against the backdrop of the dynamic East Asian economies. Spurts of growth were often followed by bust and stagnation. Not surprisingly absolute poverty among a significant proportion of the population has persisted. The country’s real per capita GDP at the turn of the 21<sup>st</sup> century was just about the same as that in the early 1980s, which also is partly attributed to unabated population growth” (ArsenioBalicsan, Ernesto Pernia ERD Policy Brief No.5 Issued February 2002).</span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;"> </span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">There is an existing rift; on one side, there are those who state that there is no existing population problem and, therefore that there is no need to act or study it. On the other, some view population growth as the principal cause of poverty.</span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;"> </span></h3>\r\n<h3><span style="color: #ffffff;">Poverty is a vast complex phenomenon, and many factors are responsible for it. Rapid population growth alone cannot explain poverty. Bad governance, high wealth and income inequality and weak economic growth rate are the main cause. But rapid population growth and fertility rates, especially among the poor exacerbates it.</span></h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[/two_third]', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-18 06:45:22', '2014-12-18 06:45:22', '', 5, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2290', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2291, 1, '2014-12-18 06:46:14', '2014-12-18 06:46:14', '[two_third]The debate over the juxtaposition of population issue and poverty may be almost as old as population itself and, in the view of the increasing trend tow­ards its complete regulation. Not surprisingly, and is generally recognized by contemporary writers on this topic, the philosophical and moral arguments for or against population issue/s have remained remarkably unchanged since the beginning of the debate.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“For the most part of the past century, the Philippine economy performed poorly, especially against the backdrop of the dynamic East Asian economies. Spurts of growth were often followed by bust and stagnation. Not surprisingly absolute poverty among a significant proportion of the population has persisted. The country’s real per capita GDP at the turn of the 21<sup>st</sup> century was just about the same as that in the early 1980s, which also is partly attributed to unabated population growth” (ArsenioBalicsan, Ernesto Pernia ERD Policy Brief No.5 Issued February 2002).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere is an existing rift; on one side, there are those who state that there is no existing population problem and, therefore that there is no need to act or study it. On the other, some view population growth as the principal cause of poverty.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPoverty is a vast complex phenomenon, and many factors are responsible for it. Rapid population growth alone cannot explain poverty. Bad governance, high wealth and income inequality and weak economic growth rate are the main cause. But rapid population growth and fertility rates, especially among the poor exacerbates it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn general terms high population is seen as an aggregate for poverty. High population rise counters even the slightest economic growth rendering it barely felt. Particular attention goes to the shift over time in the association across countries between low income and high fertility and mortality rates. These effects operate at the national level by influencing factor and product prices and the per capita availability of investment resources; as the poor are usually the last in line for jobs, school places and public health services, rapid population growth hurts them disproportionately. They also operate at the family level, by reducing parents'' per-child investments in health and education; since the poor tend to have large families, poor children are often particularly disadvantaged.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSufficient dissemination of information about safe intercourse and acts of coitus is key to spread awareness at a macro level. Bills such as the Reproductive Health (RH) bill are needed to provide assistance especially to those in the poor sector in regards with proper family planning. Provide universal access to safe and effective contraceptive options for both sexes in all ranks of society. Lack of access to good family planning services is among the largest hindrance in assuring that each child will and can be supported by his/her parent.<strong> Guarantee education through secondary school for all.</strong> In every culture, people who have completed at least some secondary school have fewer children on average, and have children later in life, than do people who have less education. End all policies that reward parents financially based on the number of children they have. Tax-breaks for parents with a higher number of children should be abolished as this proposes a positive incentive and reinforces birth of more children. The governments can preserve and even increase tax and other financial benefits aimed at helping parents by linking these not to the number of children they have, but to parenthood status itself.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n[/two_third]', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-18 06:46:14', '2014-12-18 06:46:14', '', 5, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2291', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2292, 1, '2014-12-18 06:47:36', '2014-12-18 06:47:36', '[two_third]<span style="color: #ffffff;">The debate over the juxtaposition of population issue and poverty may be almost as old as population itself and, in the view of the increasing trend tow­ards its complete regulation. Not surprisingly, and is generally recognized by contemporary writers on this topic, the philosophical and moral arguments for or against population issue/s have remained remarkably unchanged since the beginning of the debate. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #ffffff;">“For the most part of the past century, the Philippine economy performed poorly, especially against the backdrop of the dynamic East Asian economies. Spurts of growth were often followed by bust and stagnation. Not surprisingly absolute poverty among a significant proportion of the population has persisted. The country’s real per capita GDP at the turn of the 21<sup>st</sup> century was just about the same as that in the early 1980s, which also is partly attributed to unabated population growth” (ArsenioBalicsan, Ernesto Pernia ERD Policy Brief No.5 Issued February 2002). </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #ffffff;">There is an existing rift; on one side, there are those who state that there is no existing population problem and, therefore that there is no need to act or study it. On the other, some view population growth as the principal cause of poverty. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #ffffff;">Poverty is a vast complex phenomenon, and many factors are responsible for it. Rapid population growth alone cannot explain poverty. Bad governance, high wealth and income inequality and weak economic growth rate are the main cause. But rapid population growth and fertility rates, especially among the poor exacerbates it. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #ffffff;">In general terms high population is seen as an aggregate for poverty. High population rise counters even the slightest economic growth rendering it barely felt. Particular attention goes to the shift over time in the association across countries between low income and high fertility and mortality rates. These effects operate at the national level by influencing factor and product prices and the per capita availability of investment resources; as the poor are usually the last in line for jobs, school places and public health services, rapid population growth hurts them disproportionately. They also operate at the family level, by reducing parents'' per-child investments in health and education; since the poor tend to have large families, poor children are often particularly disadvantaged. </span>\r\n\r\n[/two_third]', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-12-18 06:47:36', '2014-12-18 06:47:36', '', 5, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2292', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
